{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503272"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:57:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:57:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1963"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583078","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583078"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:06:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:06:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1963"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1963"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.61,0.14,0.15,0.07,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1963"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111270"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1963"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1963"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93402"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2936"},{"type":"tags","id":"3060"},{"type":"tags","id":"4019"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"785"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10805"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11029"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111270","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111270"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old woman urgently seeks a repeat prescription of oxazepam during her GP visit, citing distress due to running out of the drug the previous night, resulting in severe sleep deprivation and physical discomfort. Prescribed for three years following her husband\u0027s death, oxazepam initially provided significant relief, but its efficacy has waned over the past year. Despite attempts to discontinue, she has struggled with withdrawal symptoms such as severe headache, rapid heartbeat, shaking hands, and a general feeling of being unsteady, making it difficult to sleep and function the next morning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe GP, recognising the need for a careful approach, plans to slowly discontinue the benzodiazepines to avoid withdrawal symptoms. The strategy involves substituting oxazepam with another benzodiazepine having a longer half-life.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be most suitable?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diazepam","Alprazolam","Oxazepam","Midazolam","Triazolam"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBenzodiazepines operate by augmenting the impact of \u03b3-aminobutyric acid (GABA) through positive allosteric modulation of the GABA\u003Csub\u003EA\u003C/sub\u003E receptor, diminishing neuronal excitability and inducing a calming effect. They may be categorised based on their half-life into short-, intermediate- and long-acting benzodiazepines. Short-acting benzodiazepines have a median elimination half-life of 1-12 hours, intermediate-acting benzodiazepines average 12-40 hours, and long-acting benzodiazepines range from 40-250 hours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate benzodiazepine in this context is \u003Cstrong\u003Ediazepam\u003C/strong\u003E with half-life of 20-100 hours. The slower elimination of diazepam creates a smoother taper in blood levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlprazolam\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eoxazepam\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Etemazepam\u003C/strong\u003E exhibit short half-lives (approximately 6-12 hours). \u003Cstrong\u003EMidazolam\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Etriazolam\u003C/strong\u003E both have very short half-lives (2-5 hours).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETriazolam is useful in managing patients with transient, severe, or disabling insomnia. Midazolam serves as a short-acting sedative agent during short procedures, induction of anesthesia, and for prolonged sedation in intensive care units.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor patients using benzodiazepines for less than four weeks, discontinuation without tapering may be feasible. Withdrawal is possible for long-term users, and a gradual reduction is advised to mitigate withdrawal symptoms, especially when usage surpasses eight weeks. Symptoms may manifest in 1\u20132 days for shorter half-life agents, whereas for those with longer half-lives, symptoms may not arise until 3\u20137 days. A typical initial withdrawal step involves substituting diazepam for the current benzodiazepine to facilitate a smoother taper in blood level due to its slower elimination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther pharmacotherapy has limited evidence in benzodiazepine withdrawal - often it is for symptom management only.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Slow discontinuation of benzodiazepines is recommended to avoid withdrawal symptoms (eg rebound anxiety, agitation, insomnia or seizures) particularly when use exceeds eight weeks.","A common first step in withdrawal is to substitute diazepam for the benzodiazepine being taken.\u00a0The slower elimination of diazepam creates a smoother taper in blood level."],"references":["Drug and Alcohol Services South Australia (DASSA), 2014. \u2018Benzodiazepine equivalents\u2019, accessed 25/5/20, https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/","Griffin CE, Kaye AM, Bueno FR, Kaye AD. Benzodiazepine pharmacology and central nervous system\u2013mediated effects. Ochsner Journal. 2013 Jun 20;13(2):214-23. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3684331/","Soyka M. Treatment of benzodiazepine dependence. New England Journal of Medicine. 2017 Mar 23;376(12):1147-57. https://www.nejm.org/doi/10.1056/NEJMra1611832","102\u0027 https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/drugs-of-dependence/part-b/discontinuing-benzodiazepines"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93402"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1963"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93402"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-12T00:33:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-12T00:33:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1963"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111270"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attri